## Plan

**Approach:** Add ONE new hand-written guide `docs/gates.md` ("Gate reviewer records") that documents the now-shipped gate-capture + gate-display behavior, plus three small linking edits (index + two one-line cross-links). A new guide is the cleanest fit: gates are a distinct concept (a review axis orthogonal to stage producers) that spans BOTH `capture-gate` (write) and `run show` (read), so folding half into `capture.md` and half into `run.md` would split one concept across two guides and bury it. A dedicated guide mirrors the existing one-topic-per-file pattern (init/capture/run/bench/gc/reindex) and gives a single place to draw the producer-vs-reviewer distinction. The guide SUMMARIZES the schema and seat conventions and LINKS the planning docs for full detail; it does not duplicate them. Examples are copied verbatim from the real built binary and the real DTO, never hand-invented.

**Files:**
- docs/gates.md - NEW hand-written guide. Sections:
  1. Intro: what a gate record is (a structured review-gate ATTEMPT appended to a run; manifest_version bumps to 3 when gates are present).
  2. "Producer vs reviewer identity" — the load-bearing distinction (AC#2): stage `produced_by`/`harness`/`model` answer WHO PRODUCED an artifact; a gate's seats answer WHO REVIEWED it. Gates are top-level, not nested under a stage, and are NOT producers (a gate may review several stages, e.g. implement.r1 reviews both `diff` and `verify`). Cite both as different axes.
  3. "Capture a gate attempt" — `etude capture-gate --run <id> --gate-file <path|->`; a real minimal gate-file JSON skeleton using the actual DTO field names from internal/cli/capture.go gateInputJSON (gate_id/phase/round/tier/status/reviewed_stages/seats[seat,harness{name,version},provider{name,model},verdict,required,optional,failure_note,raw_output{role,path,media_type},timestamp]/decision{escalation_reason,degraded_reason,deferred_beads}); note raw_output is a FILE PATH resolved into the content-addressed store; one gate per existing run (must attach to an existing run).
  4. "Provider, model, and harness fields" (AC#3) — the per-seat conventions table mirrored from the runbook, INCLUDING the pilms row (seat=pilms, harness=pi, provider.name=lmstudio, provider.model=qwen/qwen3.6-35b-a3b) alongside opus/gemini/codex; one sentence on the six verdicts (go/block/failed/empty/malfunction/disregarded) with a link to the schema for full semantics; note failure_note is required for non-go/block verdicts.
  5. "Inspect gate attempts" — `etude run show <id>` renders each gate after the stages; paste a REAL excerpt copied verbatim from `./bin/etude run show etude-roadmap.2.4` (plan.r1 BLOCK->rerun with the pilms disregarded/degraded line, then plan.r2 pass), showing gate/phase/round/tier/status/reviewed/degraded and per-seat provider/harness/verdict/required/optional/note.
  6. "Reference & further reading" — link the generated per-command pages docs/cli/etude_capture-gate.md and docs/cli/etude_run_show.md (flags only; generated, do not edit), the schema spec docs/plans/product/gate-reviewer-record-schema.md (full field semantics), and the dogfood runbook docs/plans/dogfood/review-gate-runbook.md (the process for producing these records while dogfooding).
- docs/README.md - add one "Sections" list entry linking gates.md, placed after Runs (e.g. "[Gates](gates.md) - capture and inspect review-gate reviewer records on a run.").
- docs/run.md - add one cross-link line in the "Show a run" area pointing to gates.md for the gate section that `run show` now renders.
- docs/capture.md - add one cross-link line noting `etude capture-gate` records reviewer gate attempts, see gates.md.

